# Canonical CLI Scoping — the standard for all CLI/adapter projects

> **Core Principle:** Every CLI we build is operated by humans under stress. Every CLI must be inspectable (doctor), healable (repair), explainable (help/why), and observable (--watch/--json) — by default, not as a future epic.
>
> **Reference exemplars:** `ntm` (70+ subcommands), `br`/beads (doctor + repair + schema), `cm` (validate + audit + provenance + self-documentation).

## Core Commands

The standard mandates these command names on EVERY CLI:

| Command | Purpose | Mandatory |
|---|---|---|
| `<cli> doctor [--fix] [--scope <subsystem>]` | Diagnose all subsystems, optionally repair | YES |
| `<cli> health [--watch -i N] [--json]` | Single-shot status, monitoring loop | YES |
| `<cli> repair --scope <subsystem> [--dry-run] [--apply]` | Idempotent fix for known failures | YES |
| `<cli> validate <thing>` | Pure-read verification | If state-handling |
| `<cli> audit` | Show recent mutations with provenance | If state-handling |
| `<cli> why <id>` | Provenance trace for one object | If state-handling |
| `<cli> --info` | Version + paths + env + deps dump | YES |
| `<cli> --examples` (or `examples`) | Curated workflow examples | YES |
| `<cli> quickstart` | Self-documentation for new operators | YES |
| `<cli> help <topic>` | Topic-based manual | YES |
| `<cli> completion <shell>` | Shell completion script | YES |
| `<cli> upstream-report <adapter>` | Draft upstream issue (if wraps upstream) | If aggregator |
| `<cli> doctor <adapter>` | Per-adapter scoped diagnosis | If aggregator |

## Quick Start

```bash
# Verify a candidate CLI follows the standard
bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/check-cli-scoping.sh ntm    # PASS reference
bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/check-cli-scoping.sh br     # PARTIAL reference; expected to flag gaps

# CI gate a candidate CLI against the v0.2 checklist
bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/ci-gate-cli-scoping.sh <cli>

# Score a candidate CLI against the phase 2-4 990+ bar
bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/canonical-cli-scorecard.sh \
  score <cli> --domain-exit-codes --json

# Prove this skill's own scorer/regression ladder is above the close bar
bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/canonical-cli-scorecard.sh \
  skill-score canonical-cli-scoping --json

# In a new CLI bead, copy the §"Implementation checklist" into the bead body as the acceptance gate
# Workers MUST report each gate's PASS/FAIL in the callback contract

# Before a fourth implementation dispatch on a repeated shadowing class, run from the affected repo
THIRD_STRIKE_REPO_ROOT=/path/to/affected/repo bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/check-third-strike.sh <bead-id> list-shadow-after-third-strike
```

## Phase 2-4 Scorer And Regression Ladder

The phase 1 checker answers "does this CLI expose the expected surface?" The
phase 2-4 scorer answers "is the surface strong enough for a stressed operator
or fresh worker to use without guessing?"

Run:

```bash
bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/canonical-cli-scorecard.sh \
  score <cli> --domain-exit-codes --json

bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/canonical-cli-scorecard.sh \
  regression-ladder --json

bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/canonical-cli-scorecard.sh \
  fresh-agent-simulation --json
```

The scorer emits a `canonical-cli-scorecard.result/v1` envelope and a
`composite_score` from 0-1000. A candidate CLI is 990+ only when these dimensions
all clear the bar:

| Dimension | Contract |
|---|---|
| `doctor_health_repair_contract` | `doctor`, `health`, `repair`, and `repair --dry-run` are present and mechanically probed. |
| `self_doc_content_minimums` | `--info`, `--examples`, `quickstart`, `help <topic>`, and `completion` have substantive content, not empty stubs. |
| `dry_run_json_fixture` | `repair --dry-run --json` returns JSON, marks dry-run/planned/noop state, and reports zero actual actions. |
| `domain_exit_code_validator` | Opt-in validator checks `help exit-codes` or `--exit-codes` for success, usage, transient/retry, and domain-class semantics. |
| `regression_ladder` | Golden good fixture, wrong-but-legible corpus, and single-rule mutation fixtures are present. |
| `phase4_asymptote` | Intent inference, self-application exemplar, cross-skill consistency, and fresh-agent simulation are documented and executable. |

### R-002 reviewer workflow

`canonical-cli-scorecard.sh score <cli> --json` is the reviewer workflow. It
wraps `check-cli-scoping.sh`, adds content floors, and returns dimension-level
evidence so a reviewer can say exactly why a candidate scores below 990. This is
the local equivalent of a validator subagent when a pane cannot spawn
subagents.

### R-005/R-006/R-008 hardening

- R-005 self-doc minimums: every self-documentation surface must contain enough
  words and the right operator terms to distinguish a real manual from a flag
  stub.
- R-006 dry-run JSON fixture: mutating CLIs must make `repair --dry-run --json`
  parseable and prove that `actual_actions` is empty during dry-run.
- R-008 domain exit-code validator: candidates opt in with
  `--domain-exit-codes`; the scorer then requires a documented domain table.

### Regression resistance

The regression ladder is pinned by
`tests/test_canonical_cli_scorecard.sh`:

- golden fixture scores 990+;
- wrong-but-legible fixture fails below 990;
- single-rule drift in dry-run JSON or exit-code docs is caught;
- `regression-ladder`, `fresh-agent-simulation`, `skill-score`, and
  `audit-top-skills` modes emit pass envelopes.

### Phase 4 asymptote

The fresh-agent simulation is intentionally concrete. A new worker who has only
this skill can run `score <cli> --json`, inspect dimensions below 990, repair or
bead the gap, then rerun `skill-score canonical-cli-scoping --json`. Cross-skill
consistency is checked against `agent-ergonomics-cli`, `readme-writing`, and
`testing-conformance-harnesses`: those skills should route CLI authoring back to
this scorer instead of minting separate standards.

### Top-10 fleet skill audit

After this skill scores 990+, rerun:

```bash
bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/canonical-cli-scorecard.sh \
  audit-top-skills --json
```

The audit records the top ten routing surfaces and verifies non-CLI skills route
operator-command authoring back to canonical-cli-scoping.

## File-Length Thresholds

Canonical CLI work includes file shape, not only command shape. Files that grow
beyond these thresholds must be split before the CLI surface is considered
maintainable operator substrate:

| Language / artifact | Threshold | Routing when exceeded |
|---|---:|---|
| Bash / shell | 500 lines | Extract sourced libraries under `lib/` or per-subcommand helpers; leave the executable as a thin dispatcher. |
| Python | 400 lines | Apply `python-best-practices` module/package structure, typed boundaries, and fixture-backed tests. |
| Rust | 500 lines | Apply `rust-best-practices` module boundaries, typed domain errors, and `cargo test`/`clippy` gates. |
| Markdown doctrine/docs | 1500 lines | Split by audience or lifecycle stage unless it is a deliberate canonical doctrine archive. |

Legitimate exceptions require an in-file receipt:

```text
# canonical-cli-scoping-allow-large: <reason>
```

Accepted reasons include generated code, append-only canonical doctrine, and
reviewed migration archives. The exception is not silent: `flywheel-loop doctor
--json` still reports it under `file_length.allowed_oversized_files`.

## v0.2 hardening modules

For implementation details that would bloat this trigger skill, load
[references/V0.2-HARDENING.md](references/V0.2-HARDENING.md) when the task
involves:

- renaming a colliding `console_script` with rollback or compatibility shim;
- Rust, Node, or Python CLI implementation examples;
- CI checklist gates;
