## THE EXACT PROMPT

When dispatching a CLI/adapter bead to a worker, paste this verbatim into the dispatch packet's BEAD-ANATOMY section:

```
This bead delivers a CLI surface. Per ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/SKILL.md, your callback MUST report PASS/FAIL for every gate in §"Implementation checklist":
  - doctor / health / repair triad
  - validate / audit / why subsidiary
  - --info / --examples / quickstart / help <topic> / completion
  - --json everywhere + universal exit codes
  - --dry-run + --explain on mutating ops
  - per-adapter scoping (if aggregator)
  - upstream-report <adapter> (if wraps upstream)

Use `bash ~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/check-cli-scoping.sh` as a quick sanity probe. Reference exemplars: ntm, br, cm, gh.

NAME-COLLISION PRECHECK (mandatory): before claiming any console_script entrypoint name N, run `which N` AND verify it returns nothing OR a clearly different binary you own. The B1.5/cm session-2026-05-01 trauma class is fully captured at SKILL.md §"Anti-pattern from session 2026-05-01" — don't repeat it.

THIRD-STRIKE PRECHECK (mandatory after repeated callback drift): before dispatching another implementation bead on a list-shadow/name-shadow/function-object class, run `~/.claude/skills/canonical-cli-scoping/scripts/check-third-strike.sh <bead-id> <trauma-class>` from the affected implementation repo, or set `THIRD_STRIKE_REPO_ROOT=/path/to/affected/repo`. If it blocks, run `/planning-workflow`, freeze evidence, and make the next implementation bead depend on the planning artifact.

Use ultrathink before authoring the dispatch contract.
```

## When to apply

EVERY new CLI or significant CLI extension. EVERY adapter-based aggregator (where the CLI proxies to N upstream substrates). EVERY operator-facing tool that runs in production.

If you're tempted to ship a CLI without the triad below, file a bead instead and use the standard. Do not ship a partial-scoping CLI.

## The 3+3+1 triad doctrine

### Mandatory triad (every CLI)

| Command | Purpose | Output | Exit codes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `<cli> doctor` | Run diagnostics across ALL subsystems. Optionally repair (`--fix`). Default: report-only. | Per-subsystem PASS/WARN/FAIL with stack snippet on FAIL. `--json` machine-readable. | 0=all green, 1=at least one FAIL, 2=usage error |
| `<cli> health` | Single-shot status of the running system. Lighter than doctor. Suitable for monitoring loops. | Aggregate health + per-subsystem one-liner. `--json` + `--watch -i N`. | 0=green, 1=degraded, 3=critical |
| `<cli> repair [--scope <subsystem>]` | Idempotent fix for known failure modes. Reads doctor's failure-class taxonomy. `--dry-run` mandatory. | Per-action: PLANNED → APPLIED or SKIPPED + reason. | 0=no-op or success, 1=at least one repair failed |

### Subsidiary triad (every CLI handling state)

**State-handling trigger:** a CLI is state-handling when it reads, writes, or
derives operator decisions from a file, database, remote API, queue, daemon,
cache, lock, credential store, or other substrate outside its own process-local
memory. If the CLI can leave durable residue, mutate shared state, or answer
"why did this object/status/config become this way?", it needs the subsidiary
triad. If the CLI is a pure calculator/formatter that consumes stdin/argv and
emits stdout without consulting external state, document that exemption in
`--info` or root help.

| Command | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `<cli> validate <thing>` | Verify config/spec/input WITHOUT executing. Pure read. |
| `<cli> audit` | Show recent state mutations with provenance (who, when, why, sha). |
| `<cli> why <id>` | Provenance trace for a single object: where it came from, what changed, evidence. |

See [references/STATE-HANDLING-EXAMPLES.md](references/STATE-HANDLING-EXAMPLES.md)
for worked yes/no examples and a small classification corpus to pin the trigger
against worker drift.

### Self-documentation (every CLI)

| Command/flag | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `<cli> --info` | Version, config paths, env vars, dependencies, runtime sha. One-shot diagnostic dump. |
| `<cli> --examples` (or `<cli> examples`) | Curated workflow examples. Not the same as `--help`. Use cases, not flags. |
| `<cli> quickstart` | "Explain this system to a new agent/operator." Self-documentation as a command. |
| `<cli> help <topic>` | Topic-based operator manual. Per-subsystem when applicable. NOT the same as `--help`. |
| `<cli> completion <shell>` | Generate completion script. Mandatory; no excuses. |

## Shape Calibration v1 (ratified 2026-05-10 cross-orch P1 CONTRACT)

**Spec edit:** the canonical-cli-scoping checker recognizes EITHER flag-style OR subcommand-style as canonical for 7 of the 13 dimensions. The motivation: clap-derive Rust CLIs (e.g., `beads_rust`) and similar idioms ship the same surface under subcommands rather than flags. Both shapes deliver the spec's intent; the checker should not punish style.

**Authority:** ratified bilaterally between flywheel:1 + skillos:1 under cross-orch-anti-divergence-v1.0.0 P1 CONTRACT class on 2026-05-10T18:15Z. Ledger entry at `~/.local/state/cross-orch-protocols/registry.jsonl` 2026-05-10T18:15:00Z.

### 13-dimension calibration table

| # | Dimension | Flag-style (literal) | Subcommand-style (calibrated equivalent) | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | doctor | `<cli> doctor` | same | no calibration |
| 2 | health | `<cli> health` | `<cli> doctor` (with health-class checks emitted in JSON envelope) OR `<cli> doctor --filter=health` | doctor that returns health-class results in its envelope satisfies the dim |
| 3 | repair | `<cli> repair` | `<cli> doctor --apply` OR `<cli> doctor repair` | doctor surface admits repair via documented flag/subcommand |
| 4 | repair --dry-run | `<cli> repair --dry-run` | dry-run discipline exists somewhere on the mutating surface | refined: NOT `--dry-run --apply` (oxymoronic combo); MUST exist on `repair` OR `doctor` OR global flag |
| 5 | validate | `<cli> validate <thing>` | `<cli> lint`, `<cli> check <thing>` | semantic equivalence; verify-without-mutating is the gate |
| 6 | audit | `<cli> audit` | same | no calibration |
| 7 | why | `<cli> why <id>` | `<cli> show <id>` (with provenance: created/updated/source/deps) OR `<cli> trace <id>` | functional equivalence; "why does this object exist" is the gate |
| 8 | --json | global `--json` flag | global `--json` flag OR `--format json` (multi-format support is SUPERSET) | accept superset |
| 9 | --info | `<cli> --info` flag | `<cli> info` SUBCOMMAND emitting same envelope shape (version, config_paths, env, deps, runtime_sha) | functional equivalence; envelope content is gate |
| 10 | examples | `<cli> --examples` flag OR `<cli> examples` subcommand | OR via documented artifact path (`agent_baseline/`, `EXAMPLES.md`) | discoverability calibration; curated workflows must be DISCOVERABLE |
| 11 | quickstart | `<cli> quickstart` | same — MANDATORY, no calibration | every CLI provides operator onboarding surface |
| 12 | help <topic> | `<cli> help <topic>` (topic-mode, NOT subcommand-help) | NO calibration — topic-help and subcommand-help are distinct surfaces | mandatory; topic-help covers concepts, subcommand-help covers usage |
| 13 | completion | `<cli> completion <shell>` | `<cli> completions <shell>` (plural) + clap_complete unstable-dynamic | refined: also requires emitted script parses under `<shell> -n -` |

### Refinements ratified within v1 calibration

**Dim 4 safety refinement:** `--dry-run --apply` combination is oxymoronic and explicitly REJECTED. Acceptable shapes: `<cli> repair --dry-run`, `<cli> doctor --dry-run` (no concurrent --apply), `<cli> <mutating-cmd> --dry-run`, or global `<cli> --dry-run` flag.

**Dim 13 validity refinement:** completion subcommand exists AND emitted completion script parses validly under target shell. Test command: `<cli> completion bash | bash -n -` exits 0. Catches the failure class where `completion bash` emits broken syntax (silent fail in production).

### Subcommand-style detection probe

```bash
# For each calibrated dim, check both shapes:
# Flag form:
<cli> --info >/dev/null 2>&1 && PASS_LITERAL=1
# Subcommand form:
<cli> info --help >/dev/null 2>&1 && PASS_CALIBRATED=1
# Either passes → dim PASS
```

### What this calibration is NOT

- NOT a relaxation of the spec. The 13 dimensions stay 13. The intent stays.
- NOT a free pass for poor implementations. Dim 11 (quickstart), Dim 12 (help-topic), and Dim 4 (dry-run safety) remain mandatory and uncalibrated.
- NOT contingent on language. Both bash and Rust (and TS, etc.) impls that satisfy EITHER shape pass.

