## Adapter-scoping (for aggregator CLIs)

**Rule:** If the CLI proxies to N upstream substrates (e.g., `mem` aggregating from `cm + cass + ks + memory + cards`), the doctor/health/repair triad MUST be ALSO scoped per-adapter.

```
mem doctor              # Aggregate report across all 5 adapters
mem doctor cass         # Just the cass adapter
mem doctor --adapter cass --fix
mem health              # Aggregate
mem health cm --json    # Single adapter, JSON
mem repair --scope cards --dry-run
```

Per-adapter contract:
1. `mem doctor <adapter>` MUST exit cleanly (0 or 1) even if the adapter is dead — never crash on probe.
2. `mem doctor <adapter>` MUST distinguish: `OK | DEGRADED | DOWN | NOT_CONFIGURED | UPSTREAM_BUG`.
3. `UPSTREAM_BUG` triggers `<cli> upstream-report <adapter>` (next section).

## Upstream-bug surfacing (for adapter aggregators)

When an adapter wraps an upstream tool (e.g., mem.adapters.cm wraps Jeff's `cm` binary), the CLI MUST be capable of generating an upstream-issue draft:

```
mem upstream-report cm              # Generates .planning/upstream-issues/cm-<sha>.md
mem upstream-report cm --apply      # Files the issue (requires APPROVE=yes)
```

The draft includes: reproduction steps, exact error captured, version of upstream tool, our wrapper version, suggested fix or workaround. Never auto-file without `--apply`. Always review.

This is how we stay aligned with upstream maintainers (Jeff, etc.) instead of accumulating local hacks.

## Output discipline (every command)

**Mandatory flags:**
- `--json` everywhere. Machine-readable mode is not optional.
- `--no-color` and `--no-emoji` for log/CI capture.
- `--width <n>` for non-TTY environments.

**Mandatory schema discipline:**
- Every JSON output validates against a published schema.
- `<cli> schema <command>` emits the schema for that command's output.
- (Reference: `br schema` does this.)

**Exit codes (universal):**
| Code | Meaning |
|---|---|
| 0 | Success. |
| 1 | Failure (domain-specific; expected failure mode). |
| 2 | Usage error (bad args, missing required, conflicting flags). |
| 3 | Transient/upstream/network failure (caller may retry). |
| 4 | Blocked by gate (e.g., `--allow-secret`, `APPROVE=yes`). |
| 5+ | Domain-specific. Document in --help. |

**errJSONFailure pattern (Jeff ntm#125, 2026-05-08):** when a CLI emits a JSON
failure envelope, `success:false` MUST be paired with a non-zero exit code. JSON
is the machine-readable error surface; the exit code is the shell-callable gate.
Both fire together; never JSON-XOR-exit. Stderr decoration such as `Error: ...`
is suppressed when a JSON envelope is present — the caller chooses the surface.
Shell wrappers must gate on exit code first and read the JSON envelope only for
detail.

## Jeff Delta: Domain-Grouped Exit Codes

> **Delta source:** `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/error/structured.rs:203-256` (`impl ErrorCode { pub const fn exit_code(&self) -> i32 }`). Pinning tests at `structured.rs:1013-1020` and `error/mod.rs:362-382`.
>
> **Why:** the universal table above tells operators *that* a CLI failed; Jeff's substrate adds **per-domain integer codes** so shell scripts can branch on the failure class without parsing JSON, CI gates can ratchet on a single domain, and agents can choose retry-vs-report-vs-escalate from `$?` alone.

Beyond the `0/1/2/3/4` universal codes, Jeff's `beads_rust` exits with one integer per domain:

| Exit | Domain | Sample variants |
|---:|---|---|
| 1 | Internal / unknown | `INTERNAL_ERROR` |
| 2 | Database (and clap usage error, by convention) | `DATABASE_NOT_FOUND`, `DATABASE_LOCKED`, `SCHEMA_MISMATCH`, `NOT_INITIALIZED` |
| 3 | Issue / operational lookup | `ISSUE_NOT_FOUND`, `AMBIGUOUS_ID`, `ID_COLLISION`, `NOTHING_TO_DO` |
| 4 | Validation | `VALIDATION_FAILED`, `INVALID_STATUS`, `REQUIRED_FIELD` |
| 5 | Dependency graph | `CYCLE_DETECTED`, `DEPENDENCY_NOT_FOUND`, `HAS_DEPENDENTS` |
| 6 | Sync / JSONL | `JSONL_PARSE_ERROR`, `SYNC_CONFLICT`, `CONFLICT_MARKERS`, `PATH_TRAVERSAL` |
| 7 | Config | `CONFIG_ERROR`, `CONFIG_NOT_FOUND`, `CONFIG_PARSE_ERROR` |
| 8 | I/O / serialization | `IO_ERROR`, `JSON_ERROR`, `YAML_ERROR` |

**Adoption rules:**

1. Pick domains from your CLI's actual failure classes — the pattern is "one integer per domain", not "exactly these eight".
2. Reserve `2` for usage errors regardless (clap/git/ssh convention; Jeff folds DB into `2` because there is no usage-error class beyond clap's default).
3. Reserve `3` for transient/upstream/network failures when your CLI has a remote subsystem (host §"Output discipline" universal row 3).
4. Single source of truth: a `const fn exit_code(&self) -> i32` on the error enum, exhaustively matched. The same value powers `$?` and the `--json` `code` field.
5. Pin every variant with a unit test (`assert_eq!(ErrorCode::Foo.exit_code(), N)`); without the test the table drifts on the next variant.
6. Document the domain table in `<cli> help exit-codes` (topic-help) and in `--help`.
7. Pair this with Jeff's `is_retryable` companion (`structured.rs:189-201`) so agents know which domains are safe to auto-retry.

**Full reference + adoption checklist + anti-patterns:** [references/JEFF-EXIT-CODES.md](references/JEFF-EXIT-CODES.md).

## Jeff Delta: doctor as Namespace

> **Delta source:** `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/cli/commands/doctor.rs` (named `check_*` probe functions) + `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/cli/mod.rs:2481-2491` (`DoctorArgs`).
>
> **Why:** the §"Mandatory triad" doctor command is a single entrypoint. Jeff's substrate shows that for any CLI with ≥2 internal subsystems (not just aggregator CLIs), `doctor` is best authored as a **namespace of subsystem-scoped probes**, each implemented as a named `check_<subsystem>` function pushing onto a shared `Vec<CheckResult>`. Operators read a labeled per-subsystem report; `repair --scope <subsystem>` maps 1:1 to the named check; subsystem failures map to the domain-grouped exit codes above.

The pattern restated:

```
<cli> doctor                        # All subsystems, aggregated PASS|WARN|FAIL report
<cli> doctor <subsystem>            # One subsystem only
<cli> doctor <subsystem> --json     # Machine-readable, single subsystem
<cli> doctor --repair               # All subsystems, attempt repair on FAIL rows
<cli> repair --scope <subsystem>    # Repair one subsystem (matches doctor's name)
```

**Implementation contract:**

1. **One named `check_<subsystem>` function per subsystem.** Pure-probe — no mutation, no exit. Pushes one or more structured `CheckResult { name, status, message, findings }` records.
2. **Closed status enum, not free strings.** Jeff uses `enum CheckStatus { Pass, Warn, Fail }` (`doctor.rs:31-36`). For aggregator CLIs, expand to the host taxonomy `OK|DEGRADED|DOWN|NOT_CONFIGURED|UPSTREAM_BUG`; the closed-enum invariant stays.
3. **Subsystem identifier is shared between doctor and repair.** `<cli> repair --scope foo` repairs the failures surfaced by `<cli> doctor foo`. Names match exactly — agents pivot from diagnosis to repair by string.
4. **Subsystem names are operator-readable, not module-named.** Pick names a stressed human can map to a Slack message (`integrity`, `jsonl`, `sync_metadata`), not your crate layout.
5. **Aggregate `doctor` exits `1` if any subsystem fails** (host §"Output discipline"). When `doctor <subsystem>` is the entry point and that subsystem fails, exit with the domain code from §"Jeff Delta: Domain-Grouped Exit Codes".
6. **Classification stays separate from probing.** Jeff isolates `append_*_anomalies` helpers (`doctor.rs:334-525`) from the `check_*` probes; this lets the same probe data drive both the human report and the repair planner.

**Reference exemplar:** Jeff's `beads_rust doctor` decomposes into `check_integrity`, `check_recoverable_anomalies`, `check_null_defaults`, `check_issue_write_probe`, `check_sqlite_cli_integrity`, `check_merge_artifacts`, `check_root_gitignore`, `check_jsonl`, `check_db_count`, `check_sync_jsonl_path`, `check_sync_conflict_markers`, `check_sync_metadata`, `check_database_sidecars`, `check_recovery_artifacts` — fourteen subsystems behind one `doctor` surface, each addressable by name.

**Full reference + per-subsystem table with file:line cites + anti-patterns:** [references/JEFF-DOCTOR-NAMESPACE.md](references/JEFF-DOCTOR-NAMESPACE.md).

## Jeff Delta: TOON as JSON Peer

> **Delta source:** `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/cli/mod.rs:1275-1317` (`OutputFormat { Text, Json, Csv, Toon }` + `from_env()` precedence resolver).
> **Skillos overlay anchor:** `.flywheel/CODEX-CORE-DOCTRINE-v1.md` §3.1.
>
> **Why:** §"Output discipline" mandates `--json` everywhere. That rule was authored before TOON (Token-Optimized Object Notation) shipped as a peer encoding in Jeff's `beads_rust`, in mcp-agent-mail's server prompt, and across this fleet. When the primary consumer is an LLM agent (per §"Robot mode"), JSON-only emits pay the JSON token tax for no human-readability gain. TOON belongs at JSON's level, not as a future flag.

Every output-bearing CLI authored under skillos ownership SHALL expose a single closed enum:

```
--format text|json|toon              # basic enum (no CSV)
--format text|json|csv|toon          # full enum (when CSV applies)
```

**Adoption rules:**

1. **Closed enum, not free-string.** `clap::ValueEnum` (Rust), `Literal[...]` + `argparse choices=` (Python), `oneof` (TypeScript). Free-string `--format` flags drift.
2. **`Text` is the `#[default]` variant.** Humans get readable output without `--format`; agents and scripts opt in.
3. **TOON is a peer, not a flag.** Do NOT ship `--json` AND `--toon` as separate boolean flags — the single enum is the doctrine.
4. **CSV is optional.** Surfaces that don't list rows use the basic enum; conversion paths exist between basic and full enums (Jeff's `From<OutputFormatBasic> for OutputFormat`).
5. **Env precedence chain (when `--format` is unset):** `<CLI>_OUTPUT_FORMAT > TOON_DEFAULT_FORMAT > text`. Per-CLI env beats fleet env; unknown values fall through; never panic on bad env. Implementation mirrors Jeff's `from_env()` (`mod.rs:1289-1306`).
6. **Document the chain in `<cli> help format` (topic-help) and in `<cli> --info`.** `--info` reports the resolved format AND which precedence step resolved it.
7. **Schema emission covers TOON.** `<cli> schema <command>` describes the TOON shape, not just JSON — otherwise agents fall back to scraping and defeat the token-saving purpose.

**Full reference + adoption checklist + anti-patterns:** [references/TOON-PEER.md](references/TOON-PEER.md).

## Jeff Delta: Env Counterpart for Every Persistent Flag

> **Delta source:** `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/cli/mod.rs:1289-1316` (`OutputFormat::from_env()` is the canonical exemplar; the same env-resolver pattern recurs across `beads_rust` for path/db/sync overrides).
> **Skillos generalization:** the TOON env precedence chain is one instance of a broader Jeff doctrine — every persistent CLI flag (one whose value an operator wants to set once and forget) MUST have an env counterpart with a documented precedence order.

For any flag whose value is (a) operator-pane-scoped or fleet-default-shaped, AND (b) non-secret, AND (c) sensible to leave set across many invocations: ship an env counterpart named `<CLI>_<FLAG>` (uppercase, underscored).

| Flag | Env counterpart |
|---|---|
| `--format` | `<CLI>_OUTPUT_FORMAT` (e.g. `BR_OUTPUT_FORMAT`) |
| `--no-color` | `<CLI>_NO_COLOR` (also honor ecosystem `NO_COLOR` when present) |
| `--width` | `<CLI>_WIDTH` |
| `--scope` (default scope for repair/doctor) | `<CLI>_DEFAULT_SCOPE` |
| `--db` / `--config` path overrides | `<CLI>_DB`, `<CLI>_CONFIG` |
| `--apply` / `--force` / `--yes` / `--allow-secret` | NOT covered (mutation gate; never default-on via env) |
| `--idempotency-key` | NOT covered (per-mutation; never persistent) |

**Canonical precedence chain (every flag with both surfaces):**

```
1. Explicit --flag on CLI invocation               # always wins
2. <CLI>_<FLAG> env variable                       # CLI-specific override
3. <FLEET>_<FLAG> env variable (when applicable)   # fleet-wide default (e.g. TOON_DEFAULT_FORMAT, NO_COLOR)
4. Built-in default                                # documented; never panics on unset
```

**Adoption rules:**

1. **CLI flag always wins** — operators must override env from the command line without `unset`.
2. **Per-CLI env beats fleet env** — tune one tool without flipping the fleet.
3. **Fleet env is optional.** Don't invent `<FLEET>_<FLAG>` without ≥2 CLIs sharing the default.
4. **Built-in default is hard-coded.** Unset env → fall through; never abort.
5. **Resolver shape mirrors Jeff's `from_env()`** — pure read; returns `Option<T>`; per-step `if let Ok(value) = env::var(...)` blocks in precedence order; lowercased+trimmed parser; unknown values return `None`, never panic.
6. **NEVER for secrets, mutation gates, or per-mutation values.** Pane bleed-through silently turns mutations live or leaks tokens to subprocesses.
7. **Document in `<cli> help env` AND `<cli> --info`.** `--info` reports the resolved value AND the precedence step that resolved it. Doctor probe verifies envs parse; mis-set env is WARN, not FAIL.

**Full reference + adoption checklist + anti-patterns:** [references/ENV-COUNTERPART.md](references/ENV-COUNTERPART.md).

## Jeff Delta: Per-Subcommand Robot Allow-List

> **Delta source:** `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/cli/mod.rs:1357-1374` (`pub const fn command_requests_robot_json(cmd: &Commands) -> bool`) + per-subcommand `pub robot: bool` flags (`mod.rs:2012, 2024, 2095, 2123, 2164, 2192, 2208, 2341, 2432, 2527, 2547`); consumed at `src/output/context.rs:328`.
>
> **Why:** §"Robot mode" mandates a `robot/<query>` namespace; §"Output discipline" mandates `--json` everywhere. Neither answers: when only a *subset* of subcommands accept `--robot`, which ones are robot-aware? The wrong answer is "all of them, implicitly" (a global `--robot` flag silently includes future subcommands that haven't been audited). The Jeff answer is a closed, exhaustive match-arm allow-list — robot eligibility is a per-subcommand contract, audited at compile time.

The pattern, restated:

```rust
#[must_use]
pub const fn command_requests_robot_json(cmd: &Commands) -> bool {
    match cmd {
        Commands::Close(args)    => args.robot,
        Commands::Reopen(args)   => args.robot,
        Commands::Ready(args)    => args.robot,
        // ...one arm per robot-eligible subcommand...
        _                         => false,   // wildcard: silence is NOT robot
    }
}
```

**Adoption rules:**

1. **Allow-list, not deny-list.** Enumerate which subcommands are robot-aware by name. Wildcard `_ => false` is the safe default.
2. **One central `pub const fn` predicate.** Pure, total, statically callable from the output-mode resolver. No ambient mutation, no scattered `if args.robot` branches.
3. **Per-subcommand `--robot` flag, not a global switch.** A top-level `--robot` flag that applies to every subcommand is the deny-list anti-pattern. Reject.
4. **Wildcard returns `false`.** Adding a new subcommand never silently flips it into robot mode. Robot eligibility is reviewed at PR time.
5. **The predicate composes with the global `--json` flag, never replaces it.** `args.json || command_requests_robot_json(&args.command)` — both surfaces converge into one boolean for the output-mode resolver.
6. **Document the eligible subcommand list in `<cli> help robot` and `<cli> robot/capabilities`.** Operators and dispatching agents need to know which subcommands are robot-aware without reading source.
7. **Pin with a unit test** that asserts the predicate returns `true` for expected variants and `false` for at least one negative case.
8. **Convergence with `<cli> robot/capabilities`** (host §"Robot contract"): the capabilities listing SHOULD derive mechanically from the same predicate, so operators and the contract cannot disagree.

**Full reference + adoption checklist + anti-patterns:** [references/ROBOT-ALLOW-LIST.md](references/ROBOT-ALLOW-LIST.md).

## Jeff Delta: Repair Only When Reversible

> **Delta source:** `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/cli/commands/doctor.rs:113-116` (the `Cannot repair: ...` refusal constants), `:1091-1113` (`--allow-repeated-repair` evidence-preservation gate), `:1339-1380` (`.verification-failed.json` audit trail), `:2232-2264` (rollback-only write probe). Companion: `cli/mod.rs:2486-2490` (`--repair` and `--allow-repeated-repair` flags on `DoctorArgs`).
>
> **Why:** §"Mandatory triad" requires `repair` to be "idempotent fix for known failure modes." §"Mutation discipline" requires `--dry-run`, `--explain`, idempotency, and audit emission. Both are correct floors. Jeff's substrate adds the ceiling: **`repair` MUST refuse to act when the action is not reversible. Refusal is a first-class outcome; "applied successfully" is not always the safe outcome.** A repair that destroys evidence of the original failure cannot be debugged when it itself fails. A repair that runs without first verifying rollback is possible turns one failure into two.

Three load-bearing patterns from `beads_rust doctor --repair`:

1. **Refuse to repair when authority is unsafe.** When the source-of-truth used by repair (JSONL ledger, snapshot, replica) is itself corrupt, has merge conflict markers, or contains invalid records, repair refuses with a structured error starting `"Cannot repair: ..."` and a remediation hint. State is unchanged. Exit non-zero.
2. **Refuse to repeat a repair that previously failed verification.** When a prior `repair` run left `.verification-failed.<ts>.json` evidence on disk, the next attempt is refused until the operator explicitly opts in via `--allow-repeated-repair`. **Evidence preservation > convenience.**
3. **Probe reversibility before mutating.** For DB repairs: `BEGIN`, write a sentinel, `ROLLBACK`, verify. For filesystem repairs: snapshot affected paths before mutation. For network repairs: there is no reversibility — refuse to call repair anything that reaches outside the local trust boundary.

**Adoption rules:**

1. **Refusal is a first-class outcome.** `Cannot repair: <reason>` errors exit non-zero with a structured `--json` envelope (`{success: false, code: <DOMAIN>, reason: "..."}`); pairs with the domain exit codes from §"Jeff Delta: Domain-Grouped Exit Codes".
2. **Validate the source-of-truth before reading from it.** If repair reconstructs state, validate the source first; refuse on validation failure.
3. **Preserve evidence on failure; never overwrite.** Failed repair attempts write a `.verification-failed.<ts>.json` (or equivalent) artifact; presence on disk gates the next run.
4. **Probe reversibility before mutating** (transaction + ROLLBACK; filesystem snapshot; or refuse if external).
5. **Backups are not optional** for DB-mutating repair (per `.flywheel/CODEX-CORE-DOCTRINE-v1.md` §3.2 storage triple-backup rule); audit log references backup paths + sha.
6. **Audit emits the refusal AND the reasoning.** `phase`, `outcome=refused`, `reason`, validator findings, preserved-evidence paths.
7. **`--allow-repeated-repair` (or equivalent) is the only override.** No env var. No config flag. No `--force`. Operator types it on the command line after reviewing evidence.
8. **Document the refusal taxonomy in `<cli> help repair`.**

**Full reference + adoption checklist + anti-patterns:** [references/REPAIR-REVERSIBLE.md](references/REPAIR-REVERSIBLE.md).

## Jeff Delta: NO_COLOR Over `--no-color`

> **Delta source:** `/Users/josh/Developer/jeff-corpus/beads_rust/src/config/mod.rs:3690-3705` (canonical `should_use_color` resolver) + `src/main.rs:986-996` (compound predicate consults flag AND env presence) + `src/output/context.rs:275-355, 328-341` (every renderer honors both surfaces) + `src/main.rs:1096-1130` (`human_error_color_respects_no_color_precedence` test pins both).
> **External standard:** <https://no-color.org> — any non-empty (and per the standard, *any*-presence) value of the `NO_COLOR` environment variable disables ANSI color output, across all conformant tools.
>
> **Why:** §"Output discipline" mandates a `--no-color` flag. §"Jeff Delta: Env Counterpart for Every Persistent Flag" mandates env counterparts with the canonical "CLI flag > per-CLI env > fleet env > default" precedence. Color has one extra rule that breaks the canonical chain: **`NO_COLOR` is an external ecosystem standard. It is honored unconditionally — even when the operator did not pass `--no-color`, even when no per-CLI env counterpart exists, and even when a per-CLI counterpart is set to "use color".** This is the one documented exception to "per-CLI env beats fleet env" — fleet/ecosystem env wins for color, because users opt into color-free environments globally and expect every CLI to respect that opt-in without per-tool configuration.

**Effective precedence chain (color-specific):**

```
1. Explicit CLI flag override:  --no-color  (force off)  /  --color=always  (force on)
2. Config file color setting:   display.color = true|false  (if shipped)
3. NO_COLOR env presence:       any value → force off  (per https://no-color.org)
4. Per-CLI counterpart (rare):  e.g. BR_NO_COLOR  (lower precedence than NO_COLOR; usually not shipped)
5. Stdout/stderr is-terminal:   non-terminal → force off  (CI/log capture safety)
6. Built-in default:            color on
```

**Adoption rules:**

1. **Ship `--no-color` AND honor `NO_COLOR` env.** Both surfaces. Either alone disables color. Never one without the other.
2. **Presence is sufficient.** `env::var_os("NO_COLOR").is_some()` (Rust) / `os.environ.get("NO_COLOR") is not None` (Python) / `process.env.NO_COLOR !== undefined` (TS). Do NOT parse the value; do NOT special-case `NO_COLOR=0`/`false` — the <https://no-color.org> standard is presence-only.
3. **Centralize the predicate** in one `should_use_color()` helper. Every code path that emits ANSI consults it. Do not scatter `if cli.no_color` checks.
4. **The compound check goes in the helper, not the call sites.** Two renderers must never disagree on whether to colorize.
5. **Don't ship a per-CLI `<CLI>_NO_COLOR` env counterpart unless cross-tool conflict requires it.** If shipped, it MUST be lower precedence than `NO_COLOR`, contrary to the canonical "per-CLI env beats fleet env" rule. Document the inversion explicitly.
6. **`--json` and robot mode bypass color regardless.** Color is for human-readable output only; structured outputs never carry ANSI.
7. **Pin with a unit test:** `--no-color` alone disables, `NO_COLOR` env alone disables, non-terminal disables, and the three combine without contradiction.
8. **Document in `<cli> help format` (or `<cli> help color`) and `<cli> --info`.** `--info` reports the resolved color decision AND which surface decided.

**Full reference + adoption checklist + anti-patterns:** [references/NO_COLOR-ENV.md](references/NO_COLOR-ENV.md).

## Mutation discipline

ANY command that mutates state MUST support:
- `--dry-run`: print what would happen, exit 0.
- `--explain`: print rationale (the "why" trace) before executing.
- Idempotency: re-running with same inputs is a no-op.
- Audit-log emission: every mutation appends to `<cli> audit`.

ANY command that mutates SHARED state (cross-tree, cross-process) MUST support:
- File reservation via Agent Mail (or equivalent locking).
- Atomic write contract (temp file + fsync + os.replace).
- Backup-before-mutate with restore path documented.

### Dry-run output contract

`--dry-run --json` MUST distinguish planned and actual effects. Before
`--apply`, output only `planned_actions`, `would_write`, `would_delete`,
`would_call_external`, and `blocked_by`. After apply, output `actual_actions`,
`writes`, `deletes`, `external_calls`, and `audit_ids`. Never mix hypothetical
and executed effects in one key.

### Idempotency keys

Any mutating command that can be retried by an agent or CI MUST accept an
idempotency key (`--idempotency-key <key>` or a documented equivalent). Reusing
the key returns the original audit result instead of repeating the mutation.

## Jeff Delta: Append-Only Audit And Lineage

> **Delta source:** flywheel Jeff-pattern matrix
> `.flywheel/jeff-corpus/v1/learnings/06-skill-enhancement-matrix.md`, rank 1
> for `canonical-cli-scoping`; adopted patterns:
> `append-only-audit-log`, `callback-envelope-shape`,
> `doctor-health-repair-triad`, `frontmatter-validation`,
> `idempotency-key-fail-closed`, `lock-file-convention`,
> `schema-version-migration`, and `testing-fixture-conventions`.

State-changing CLI surfaces MUST leave an append-only lineage trail. The audit
log is not a debug log; it is the authoritative mutation ledger that lets
operators answer: what changed, who/what initiated it, which idempotency key
deduped it, which files or upstream resources were touched, and which receipt
proves the post-check.

Adoption rules:

1. **Append-only by default.** Mutations append JSONL rows to a documented audit
   ledger. Do not rewrite, truncate, or "compact" the primary ledger in normal
   operation. If compaction becomes necessary, write a migration row first and
   preserve the source ledger path and checksum.
2. **Every audit row carries lineage.** Required fields:
   `schema_version`, `ts`, `command`, `actor`, `operation`, `idempotency_key`,
   `dry_run`, `apply`, `input_hash`, `planned_actions`, `actual_actions`,
   `touched_paths`, `external_targets`, `receipt_path`, `post_check`,
   `result`, and `failure_class`.
3. **Fail closed on ambiguous idempotency.** If a mutating command accepts an
   idempotency key but cannot read the previous audit row for that key, it MUST
   refuse instead of replaying side effects. Refusal exits non-zero and emits a
   JSON failure envelope.
4. **Lock rows are lineage rows.** Cross-process mutation locks must have
   acquire/release audit rows with `lock_path`, `holder`, `ttl`, and
   `stale_lock_policy`. A lock file without audit lineage is an orphaned
   operator state.
5. **Schema migrations are ledgered.** Any audit schema bump writes a
   `schema_migration` row with `from_schema`, `to_schema`, compatibility notes,
   and the validator command. Readers must tolerate prior minor versions or
   fail with a migration hint, not a parser traceback.
6. **Callbacks remain local-contract aware.** If the CLI is used by flywheel
   workers, receipt envelopes may add lineage fields, but MUST NOT replace
   DID/DIDNT/GAPS, `mission_fitness`, `br_close_executed`, or callback delivery
   verification fields required by dispatch packets.
7. **Pin with fixture replay.** Every append-only ledger surface needs at least
   one fixture replay that proves: dry-run creates no mutation row, apply
   appends exactly one row, replay with the same idempotency key returns the
   original row, and a schema-version fixture remains readable.

Minimal audit row shape:

```json
{
  "schema_version": "mycli.audit/v1",
  "ts": "2026-05-08T00:00:00Z",
  "command": "mycli repair --scope db --apply",
  "actor": "codex",
  "operation": "repair",
  "idempotency_key": "repair-db-20260508",
  "dry_run": false,
  "apply": true,
  "input_hash": "sha256:...",
  "planned_actions": ["vacuum db"],
  "actual_actions": ["vacuum db"],
  "touched_paths": [".mycli/state.db"],
  "external_targets": [],
  "receipt_path": ".mycli/receipts/repair-db-20260508.json",
  "post_check": {"status": "pass"},
  "result": "applied",
  "failure_class": null
}
```

## Observability and long-running output

CLIs that run background work, remote operations, or multi-step repairs MUST
provide:

| Command | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `<cli> metrics [--json]` | Counters, timings, queue depth, failure classes |
| `<cli> logs [--since <dur>] [--json]` | Structured recent operator log |
| `<cli> trace <op>` | One operation's span/provenance trace |

Long-running commands MUST support NDJSON progress events on stdout:
`started`, `progress`, `warning`, `blocked`, `completed`, `failed`. Human
pretty output is allowed, but CI/agents need deterministic event streams.

## Extension and server-mode boundaries

Only add plugins when there is a stable extension contract and at least two
real downstream adapters. Plugin APIs must version their manifest schema and
provide `plugin validate`. Otherwise, keep adapters in-tree.

Server or daemon mode follows the same standard:
`<cli> serve`, `<cli> daemon status`, `<cli> daemon stop`, and `<cli> health`
must agree on process identity, socket/port, config path, and readiness.

## Discoverability for large surfaces (>20 subcommands)

Once a CLI grows past 20 subcommands, three additional surfaces become mandatory:

1. **Palette/dashboard** — interactive command picker (`ntm palette`, `ntm dashboard`).
2. **Activity/changes** — "what's happening right now" view (`ntm activity`, `ntm changes`).
3. **Triage** — "what should I do next" advisory (`bv --robot-next`, `ntm assign`).

Below 20 subcommands, --help + topic-help is enough. Above 20, humans need a UI.

## Robot mode (for CLIs operated by agents, not just humans)

> **Doctrine:** When a CLI's primary consumer is an LLM agent or another CLI rather than a human, the canonical surface is not `--help` + scrollback — it is a `robot/<query>` namespace returning stable JSON envelopes. Agents must not scrape help text or grep terminal output to determine system state; they must call canonical state queries with versioned schemas.
>
> **Reference exemplar:** `ntm` exposes 135 `--robot-*` commands (`internal/robot/capabilities.go`, registry doctrine at `docs/robot-command-registry.md`). Validated catalog of 11 high-leverage commands at `~/.claude/skills/.flywheel/...` (cataloged 2026-05-02 by pane 3 dispatch `ntm_robot_refactor_recs_2026_05_02`).

### When to add a robot namespace

EVERY CLI that meets ANY of these conditions:
- Primary consumer is an agent (orchestrator, dispatcher, scheduler, monitor)
- State queries get scraped from `--help` or scrollback by ≥2 downstream consumers
- Hand-rolled regex parsers exist anywhere in your fleet for the CLI's output
- The CLI manages live processes/sessions/agents (any "is X working?" question)

### The robot contract

Every `robot/<query>` command MUST:

| Requirement | Why |
|---|---|
| Emit `{success: bool, timestamp, version, output_format, ...}` envelope | Agents need stable framing to parse confidently |
| Publish a JSON schema retrievable via `<cli> robot/schema=<query>` | Parser contracts decouple agent code from CLI version churn |
| Maintain backward-compat schemas across CLI minor versions | Breaking schemas across point releases breaks all downstream agents |
| Use semantic state values (`WAITING|THINKING|GENERATING|ERROR|...`), never UI strings | Activity classifiers should drive state, not regex over animated spinners |
| Provide a `<cli> robot/capabilities` command that lists all robot queries with their schemas | Discovery without scraping `--help` |
| Probe live state, not stale scrollback | Agents querying state need ground truth, not what was last shown to a human |

### Mandatory robot triad (for agent-operated CLIs)

| Command | Solves | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `<cli> robot/activity` | "What is each managed entity doing right now?" | The PRIMARY truth for capacity/idle/working decisions |
| `<cli> robot/diagnose` | "Why is entity X stuck?" | Returns `overall_health`, classified problems, suggested fix commands |
| `<cli> robot/tail` | "Show me the recent output of entity X" | Replaces raw multiplexer captures or scrollback regex |

### Convergence rule (CRITICAL)

If a CLI exposes multiple robot queries that *should* agree (e.g., `robot/is-working` and `robot/activity` both reporting on pane state), they MUST share a classifier. **Disagreement is a contract violation.** File upstream issue immediately. Downstream consumers should pick ONE as authoritative and document why.

> **Trauma class:** session 2026-05-02 caught `ntm --robot-activity` reporting `THINKING` while `ntm --robot-is-working` reported `SAFE_TO_RESTART` for the same Codex pane. Activity is correct (uses 15-line live thinking window per `internal/robot/activity.go:19`); is-working consumes stale state. Filed as ntm follow-up. **Don't repeat: validate convergence between any pair of robot queries before declaring either authoritative.**

### Migration anti-pattern

Hand-rolled scrollback parsers (`tmux capture-pane | grep`, `ntm save | grep spinner_re`) are the single largest source of fleet-wide false positives. Every UI tweak in the upstream CLI breaks every downstream consumer simultaneously, silently. **Replace with robot mode the moment it ships.**

The session 2026-05-02 audit found 15 hand-rolled detectors in our flywheel substrate that should have been `--robot-activity` calls — they were responsible for self-reflection-paradox and 13hr phantom-trajectory loops.

## ALPS 2026-05-06 Trap Classes (universal-class default for every dispatch)

> **Status:** This skill is referenced as the **universal-class default** in every ZestStream dispatch packet (per `~/.claude/projects/-Users-josh-Developer-alpsinsurance/memory/feedback-bead-dispatches-must-inject-relevant-skills.md`). The traps below were each cost-paid in ALPS-Insurance work the week of 2026-05-05. None are speculative; each pins to either a memory file or a real shell invocation in the ALPS repo.
>
> **Why universal-class:** these trap classes are CLI-shape problems on operator-facing CLIs (ntm, infisical, cf-secret, gh, railway, br). Any worker invoking a shell verb in a dispatch packet inherits exposure unless the packet carries this skill.

### Trap class table

| # | Trap | Violating pattern | Canonical-compliant pattern | Why non-obvious | Evidence |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| T1 | `ntm send` queued-not-submitted | `ntm send <session> --pane=N "<prompt>"` and trust "Sent to pane" stdout | After every `ntm send`, sleep 5s then `ntm --robot-activity=<session> --panes=N` and verify `state == THINKING`; if `WAITING + codex_chevron_prompt`, re-send empty `""` to deliver Enter | "Sent to pane" reports buffer-landing, NOT submission. Codex panes have a documented queued-not-submitted bug; success stdout decouples from agent-state | `feedback-ntm-send-post-dispatch-validation-required.md` (5+ recurrences this session, 30+ min invisible stalls) |
| T2 | `infisical secrets` table-format leak | `infisical secrets ... \| awk -F= '/PATTERN/ {print $1}'` | `infisical secrets ... --format dotenv-export \| awk -F= '/^export / {print $1}'` OR `--format json \| jq -r '.[].name'` | Default output is Unicode vertical-bar table, NOT k=v. `awk -F=` parses each row as one field and silently passes ALL VALUES through. `--silent` suppresses progress not table; `2>/dev/null` doesn't help (table is on stdout) | `feedback-infisical-table-format-leaks-secrets.md` (1 rotation cost: VERCEL_API_TOKEN, VERCEL_TOKEN, VERCEL_PROTECTION_BYPASS, VERCEL_ORG_ID, VERCEL_PROJECT_ID leaked across 2 projects × 3 envs) |
| T3 | Stdout-pipeline secret leak via codex capture | `curl ... \| jq -r '.data.var.SECRET' \| python3 -c '...sanitize...'` | `curl ... > /dev/shm/sec.$$ && trap "shred -u /dev/shm/sec.$$" EXIT; python3 -c '...' < /dev/shm/sec.$$` | Codex captures the FULL stdout of `curl\|jq` into pane scrollback BEFORE the python sanitizer ever runs. Sanitized python output is moot — bare value already lives in transcript | `feedback-stdout-pipeline-leaks-secret-via-codex-capture.md` (DATABASE_URL leak during H2 diagnosis 2026-05-05T~12:00Z) |
| T4 | `gh secret list` name-only validation false-confidence | `gh secret list \| grep VERCEL_TOKEN && echo "rotation done"` | After write: (1) `gh secret list` for presence, (2) grep ALL consumers (`rg "secrets\.(LEGACY\|MODERN)" .github/workflows`), (3) **runtime probe** (`vercel projects ls` / `curl -H "Bearer $TOKEN"`) to confirm the consumer reaches the modern value | Name-presence ≠ value-correct ≠ consumer-switched. When BOTH legacy + modern names exist, `secrets.LEGACY_NAME` resolves silently to wrong token — no missing-secret error, just wrong outcomes | `feedback-token-shadowing-rotation-not-complete-without-consumer-switch.md` (3 dispatches over multiple sessions to find Vercel staging vca_/legacy split) |
| T5 | `br create` heredoc / argv multi-line body | `br create -p 1 -t task -d "Fix \`thing\` with \\n newlines and special chars"` | Write body to `/tmp/bead-$$.md`, then `br create -p 1 -t task -d "$(cat /tmp/bead-$$.md)"` — file-mediated ALWAYS for bodies with backticks/newlines | zsh parses backticks in `-d "..."` argv as command-substitution; embedded newlines truncate; no error message — just a malformed bead body | `.planning/wave-3/dispatch-log/audit-report-codex.md:106-110` — examples of long single-line `-d` invocations that work; multi-line variants caused 1 dispatch failure this session |
| T6 | `railway` without `--project --service` flags | `railway up --detach` / `railway logs -e staging` (relies on linked context) | `railway up --detach --service "$RAILWAY_SERVICE_ID" --environment "$RAILWAY_ENVIRONMENT_ID"`; `railway logs --project "$RAILWAY_PROJECT_ID" --service "$RAILWAY_SERVICE_ID"` | `railway link` state is per-cwd and survives across shells; CI runners and worker panes inherit STALE link from prior sessions; deploys land in unintended targets silently | `scripts/deploy-staging.sh:246` (`railway up --detach`) and `:282` (`railway logs -e staging` no `--service`); `scripts/deploy-production.sh:347,393` (`railway up`, `railway run --` no project/service) |
| T7 | Codex chevron `/review` template traps the callback | Worker prints clean shipping summary → `/review` template renders in chevron → operator types ntm callback, it lands inside `/review` template | After printing shipping summary, the IMMEDIATE next pane action MUST be the ntm callback (`agent-mail send` or equivalent). Don't pause. Don't render the chevron template. Validate post-callback via `--robot-activity` that pane returned to clean state | Chevron templates auto-render on idle; once rendered, next-keystroke is captured into the template input slot, not the agent prompt. Looks like callback succeeded; orphans land at flywheel:1 invisibly | 2 orphan-callback events this session (pairs with `feedback-callback-target-must-be-explicit-not-flywheel-default.md`) |
| T8 | `infisical secrets set NAME "$VALUE"` argv leak | `infisical secrets set ALPS_HUBSPOT_PAT "$TOKEN" --env production` | `printf '%s' "$TOKEN" \| infisical-set ALPS_HUBSPOT_PAT --sensitive` (stdin-only); for upstream `infisical secrets set` use `--from-stdin` if available or wrap via the `infisical-secrets` skill helper | argv values appear in `ps auxf`, shell history, process exporters, and any tracing/strace capture. `set` looks like a config command; it's actually a secret write | `scripts/deploy-staging.sh:200-216`, `scripts/deploy-production.sh:201-242` (35+ `infisical secrets set NAME "$VALUE"` invocations across both deploy scripts) |
| T9 | bash `=~` regex with `{N,M}` quantifier in `validate <subject>` arms | `[[ "$arg" =~ ^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]{4,256}$ ]]` (length-range inside the regex) | Two-check form: `local len=${#arg}; if (( len >= 4 && len <= 256 )) && [[ "$arg" =~ ^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]+$ ]]; then …` (length gate AND char-class regex, separated by `&&`). Include `observed_length:$len` in the reject envelope. | bash `=~` uses POSIX ERE which lacks `{N,M}` repetition; runtime error is `bash: invalid repetition count(s)`. Trap confuses operators coming from PCRE / `grep -P` / Python `re` where `{N,M}` is standard. Failure is RUNTIME, not parse-time — a script with this regex passes `bash -n` and only blows up when a value reaches the broken arm. | `feedback_bash_regex_no_brace_repetition.md` (META-RULE 2026-05-11); origin `.flywheel/audit/flywheel-1hshd.37/evidence.md` (`validate receipt-ref` discovery); production reference `.flywheel/scripts/idempotency-replay-guard.sh:280` (canonical two-check form in use) |

### Stdin-only secret writes (canonical)

The argv-vs-stdin distinction is not optional for secret writes. Argv is process-table-visible across the whole host; stdin is private to the parent-child pipe.

```bash
# CANONICAL (every secret write)
printf '%s' "$VALUE" | infisical-set NAME --sensitive

# CANONICAL (with cf-secret / gh secret / railway variables)
printf '%s' "$VALUE" | gh secret set NAME --body -      # gh accepts --body -
printf '%s' "$VALUE" | railway variables --set NAME=- < /dev/stdin  # service-scoped

# FORBIDDEN
infisical secrets set NAME "$VALUE"                      # argv leak (T8)
gh secret set NAME --body "$VALUE"                       # argv leak
echo "$VALUE" | infisical-set NAME                       # echo leaks via builtin trace
```

### File-mediated secret reads (canonical)

When a worker MUST introspect a secret value (URL parsing, length check, hash compare):

```bash
# CANONICAL — secret never crosses pane stdout
umask 077
cf-secret DATABASE_URL > /dev/shm/sec.$$
trap "shred -u /dev/shm/sec.$$ 2>/dev/null || rm -f /dev/shm/sec.$$" EXIT
python3 -c 'import sys; v=open("/dev/shm/sec.'"$$"'").read(); print(len(v))' < /dev/null

# BETTER — use server-side metadata (length/hash) so bare value never reaches worker
cf-secret DATABASE_URL | shasum -a 256 | cut -c1-16    # only digest in scrollback

# FORBIDDEN — codex captures stdout of curl|jq before python ever runs
curl ... | jq -r '.data.var.SECRET' | python3 -c '...'   # T3
cf-secret X | curl --data-binary @- ...                  # T3 (pipe-through-pane)
```

### Format-flag discipline (LLM-readable contexts)

When the consumer is an LLM (any dispatch packet, any worker pane, any orchestrator readback):

```bash
# CANONICAL — explicit format + key-only filter
infisical secrets --silent --domain ... --projectId ... --env <env> --format dotenv-export 2>/dev/null \
  | awk -F= '/^export / {print $1}' | sort -u
infisical secrets ... --format json | jq -r '.[].name'

# FORBIDDEN — default table format
infisical secrets ... | awk -F= '...'                    # T2: silently passes values through
infisical secrets ... | head -20                         # truncates display, values still in stream
infisical secrets ... 2>/dev/null                        # table is stdout, /dev/null is stderr
```

### Post-dispatch verification (`ntm send` discipline)

```bash
# CANONICAL — every ntm send is a 2-step transaction
ntm send "$SESSION" --pane="$N" "$PROMPT"
sleep 5
state=$(ntm --robot-activity="$SESSION" --panes="$N" --json | jq -r '.agents[0].state')
case "$state" in
  THINKING|WORKING) echo "submitted" ;;
  WAITING)
    # queued-not-submitted; deliver Enter
    ntm send "$SESSION" --pane="$N" ""
    sleep 5
    state2=$(ntm --robot-activity="$SESSION" --panes="$N" --json | jq -r '.agents[0].state')
    [[ "$state2" == "WAITING" ]] && { echo "BLOCKED: pane $N not submitting after 2 attempts"; exit 1; }
    ;;
esac

# FORBIDDEN — trust ntm stdout
ntm send "$SESSION" --pane="$N" "$PROMPT" && echo "dispatched"   # T1
```

For batched dispatches (3+ panes simultaneous): validate ALL panes after the batch, BEFORE sending standby/heartbeat-receive. Skipping this for "speed" reliably costs 30+ minutes of invisible idle.

### Codex chevron-template trap

When a worker prints a clean shipping summary, the **immediate next pane action MUST be the ntm callback or `agent-mail send`** — not a thinking pause, not a "let me also document this" detour. Once the chevron `/review` template auto-renders, the next keystroke is captured into the template input slot, not the agent prompt. The callback orphan lands at the default `flywheel:1` target and is invisible to the alpsinsurance orchestrator (pairs with `feedback-callback-target-must-be-explicit-not-flywheel-default.md`).

Operator discipline: after callback emit, run `ntm --robot-activity` to confirm the pane returned to a clean prompt state. Chevron-template-trapped panes show `codex_chevron_prompt` immediately after a "completed" log line — that pattern means the callback DID NOT land.

### Bash regex `=~` no `{N,M}` repetition (canonical two-check form)

Bash's `[[ … =~ … ]]` operator uses POSIX ERE, which **does not** support
the `{N,M}` repetition quantifier. A `validate <subject>` arm whose input
has both a length-range constraint AND a character-class constraint cannot
encode both inside one regex:

```bash
# FORBIDDEN — bash =~ does NOT support {N,M}; runtime error: bash: invalid repetition count(s)
if [[ "$arg" =~ ^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]{4,256}$ ]]; then …

# CANONICAL — split the length gate from the char-class regex
local len="${#arg}"
if (( len >= 4 && len <= 256 )) && [[ "$arg" =~ ^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]+$ ]]; then
  # ok envelope
  jq -nc --arg v "$arg" '{status:"ok", value:$v}'
else
  # reject envelope — include observed_length so callers see WHY
  jq -nc --arg v "$arg" --argjson len "$len" \
    '{status:"reject", value:$v, reason:"pattern_or_length_mismatch",
      pattern:"^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]+$", length_range:"[4, 256]",
      observed_length:$len}'
fi
```

**Why operators step on this trap:**

- Failure is RUNTIME (`bash: invalid repetition count(s)`), not parse-time.
  `bash -n script.sh` passes; the broken arm only blows up when a value
  reaches it. Test coverage that omits the validate path ships the bug.
- PCRE, `grep -P`, Python `re`, JavaScript regex, and Rust `regex` crate
  all support `{N,M}` — operators coming from those languages assume bash
  does too.
- `[[:digit:]]{N,M}` looks identical to a POSIX character class with
  repetition; it's not. Bash's ERE has POSIX bracket classes (the
  `[[:digit:]]` part), but no `{N,M}` quantifier.

**Canonical reject envelope shape** (mirrors `idempotency-replay-guard.sh:280`
production use):

```json
{
  "schema_version": "<surface>.v1",
  "command": "validate",
  "subject": "<subject>",
  "ts": "<iso>",
  "status": "reject",
  "value": "<received>",
  "reason": "pattern_or_length_mismatch",
  "pattern": "^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]+$",
  "length_range": "[4, 256]",
  "observed_length": <int>
}
```

The `observed_length` field is mandatory — without it, an operator
debugging a rejected value can't tell whether the failure was length-side
or char-class-side.

**Discovery and references:**

- META-RULE memory: `feedback_bash_regex_no_brace_repetition.md`
  (2026-05-11, surfaced via flywheel-1hshd.37 receipt-ref discovery)
- Production reference (load-bearing today):
  `.flywheel/scripts/idempotency-replay-guard.sh:280` uses the canonical
  two-check form for the `validate receipt-ref` subject
- Cross-link bead: flywheel-898ji audit at
  `.flywheel/audit/flywheel-898ji/evidence.md`

### `br create` body discipline

```bash
# CANONICAL — file-mediated body for anything multi-line or with shell-special chars
cat > /tmp/bead-$$.md <<'BODY'
Title line

Detailed body with `backticks`, "quotes", $variables, and
multiple lines.
BODY
br create -p 1 -t task -d "$(cat /tmp/bead-$$.md)"
rm -f /tmp/bead-$$.md

# FORBIDDEN — heredoc'd argv with shell-special chars
br create -p 1 -t task -d "Fix \`thing\` with \"quotes\" and
multiple lines"   # zsh parse-error class; backticks executed; \n truncates
```

### Railway scope flags (canonical)

```bash
# CANONICAL — every railway invocation carries explicit project + service + environment
railway up --detach \
  --service "$RAILWAY_SERVICE_ID" \
  --environment "$RAILWAY_ENVIRONMENT_ID"
railway logs \
  --project "$RAILWAY_PROJECT_ID" \
  --service "$RAILWAY_SERVICE_ID" \
  --environment "$RAILWAY_ENVIRONMENT_ID"
railway run \
  --service "$RAILWAY_SERVICE_ID" \
  --environment "$RAILWAY_ENVIRONMENT_ID" \
  -- python3 -c '...'

# FORBIDDEN — relies on `railway link` state of the cwd
railway up --detach                  # T6 — silently deploys to whatever was last linked
railway logs -e staging              # T6 — service unspecified
railway run -- python3 -c '...'      # T6 — no service/env scope
```

The same scope-discipline applies to every multi-substrate CLI: `vercel --token --scope`, `gh --repo`, `kubectl --context --namespace`, `aws --profile --region`, `supabase --project-ref`. If the CLI has a "linked context" mode, the canonical pattern is **always-explicit-flags-in-scripts**; reserve `link` state for human REPL use only.

### Universal-class application

Every ZestStream dispatch packet authored after 2026-05-06 carries this skill in its `Required skills (load before coding)` block:

```markdown
## Required skills (load before coding)

- `canonical-cli-scoping` — universal-class default; covers ntm queued-not-submitted (T1), infisical table-format leak (T2), stdout-pipeline secret capture (T3), gh-secret name-only false-confidence (T4), br create body discipline (T5), railway scope flags (T6), codex chevron callback trap (T7), argv secret writes (T8), bash `=~` `{N,M}` runtime trap (T9). Load FIRST before any other skill.
- `<bead-class skill 1>` — <why>
- `<bead-class skill 2>` — <why>
```

Rationale: the 8 traps above are CLI-shape, operator-pane-shape, and dispatch-shape concerns that cross-cut every bead class. Skipping the load is not a savings — it's a deferred trauma.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Why it fails | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Ship CLI without `doctor` | Operators can't diagnose; everything becomes "ssh in and grep" | Doctor is mandatory before v0.1 |
| `doctor` that crashes when subsystem is dead | Defeats the purpose — operator can't even see what's wrong | Wrap each probe in try/except, classify as DOWN, never crash |
| `repair` without `--dry-run` | Operators can't preview; one bad invocation destroys state | --dry-run is mandatory; default to dry-run if --apply absent |
| Console_script that name-collides with upstream binary (`cm` collision in pyproject.toml when Jeff's `cm` is already in PATH) | Silent breakage when venv shadows global | Always pick distinct names; verify with `which <name>` before claiming the entrypoint |
| `--json` on some commands but not others | Brittle automation, partial adoption | --json everywhere or nowhere |
| Per-adapter status hidden in aggregate output | Can't fix individual adapter; no upstream-bug attribution | Per-adapter scope mandatory for aggregator CLIs |
| `repair` that mutates without audit | No forensic trail when fix-the-fix fix breaks | Every repair appends to audit log |
| Custom error messages without exit codes | Scripting impossible | Standard exit code table mandatory |
| Help text without examples | Users don't know which flag combos work | Every --help has an Examples section with 3-5 real invocations |
| Agents scraping --help or scrollback for state | Every UI tweak silently breaks all downstream agents | If primary consumer is an agent: add a `robot/<query>` namespace with stable JSON schemas |
| Two robot queries that disagree on the same state | Downstream consumers can't trust either; trauma class accumulates silently | Robot queries that report on overlapping state MUST share a classifier; disagreement = contract violation, file upstream |
| Trust `ntm send` "Sent to pane" stdout as proof-of-submit (T1) | Codex queued-not-submitted bug strands prompts in input buffer; "success" decouples from agent state | Always sleep 5s + `--robot-activity` poll + re-send `""` if WAITING |
| `infisical secrets ... \| awk -F=` (T2) | Default Unicode-table format silently passes ALL values through | Explicit `--format dotenv-export` or `--format json` + key-only filter |
| `curl \| jq \| python3 sanitize` for secret introspection (T3) | Codex captures pre-sanitize stdout into pane scrollback | File-mediate via `/dev/shm/sec.$$` with `umask 077` + `shred -u` trap |
| `gh secret list \| grep NAME && echo done` (T4) | Name-presence ≠ value-correct ≠ consumer-switched; legacy+modern names both resolve | 3-step rotation: write / consumer-switch / runtime-probe |
| `br create -d "...multiline with \`backticks\`..."` (T5) | zsh executes backticks; newlines truncate; no error | File-mediate body: `br create -d "$(cat /tmp/bead-$$.md)"` |
| `railway up` / `railway logs` / `railway run` without `--service --project --environment` (T6) | Per-cwd `railway link` state survives across shells; CI inherits stale link | Always-explicit-flags-in-scripts; reserve `link` for human REPL |
| Worker emits clean shipping summary then pauses (T7) | Codex chevron `/review` template auto-renders; next keystroke captured into template not callback | Callback MUST be the immediate next action after summary; verify post-callback via `--robot-activity` |
| `infisical secrets set NAME "$VALUE"` (T8) | argv visible in `ps`, history, exporters, strace | Stdin-only: `printf '%s' "$VALUE" \| infisical-set NAME --sensitive` |

## Implementation checklist (use as bead acceptance gate)

Copy this to any new CLI/adapter bead:

```
DOCTOR/HEALTH/REPAIR TRIAD:
  [ ] <cli> doctor exits 0/1, --json works, never crashes
  [ ] <cli> doctor --fix idempotent, dry-run default if --apply absent
  [ ] <cli> health single-shot, --watch -i N, --json
  [ ] <cli> repair --scope <subsystem> --dry-run mandatory

VALIDATE/AUDIT/WHY:
  [ ] <cli> validate <thing> pure-read, no side effects
  [ ] <cli> audit emits structured log of mutations with provenance
  [ ] <cli> why <id> shows full provenance trace

SELF-DOC:
  [ ] <cli> --info dumps version + paths + env + deps
  [ ] <cli> --examples (or examples cmd) has 5+ curated workflows
  [ ] <cli> quickstart written for new operators
  [ ] <cli> help <topic> for each major topic
  [ ] <cli> completion <shell> generates valid completions

ADAPTER SCOPE (if aggregator):
  [ ] doctor/health/repair scoped per-adapter
  [ ] adapter status taxonomy: OK|DEGRADED|DOWN|NOT_CONFIGURED|UPSTREAM_BUG
  [ ] <cli> upstream-report <adapter> generates draft, --apply gated

OUTPUT:
  [ ] --json on every command
  [ ] --no-color, --no-emoji, --width
  [ ] schema emission for every JSON output
  [ ] standard exit code table documented in --help

MUTATION:
  [ ] --dry-run + --explain on every state-changing command
  [ ] idempotent re-run
  [ ] audit log emission
  [ ] append-only audit ledger documented and schema-versioned
  [ ] audit rows include actor, idempotency_key, touched_paths, receipt_path, post_check, result
  [ ] same idempotency key returns the original audit row instead of repeating side effects
  [ ] ambiguous idempotency/audit read failure refuses mutation with structured JSON failure
  [ ] schema migration fixture proves prior audit row versions remain readable or fail with migration hint

THIRD-STRIKE PLANNING GATE:
  [ ] repeated shadowing class checked with check-third-strike.sh before another implementation dispatch
  [ ] planning artifact exists before implementation resumes when threshold is met

DISCOVERABILITY (if >20 subcommands):
  [ ] palette/dashboard
  [ ] activity/changes view
  [ ] triage/assign advisory

ROBOT MODE (if agent-operated):
  [ ] robot/activity, robot/diagnose, robot/tail triad present
  [ ] robot/capabilities lists all robot queries with schemas
  [ ] robot/schema=<query> returns JSON schema for each
  [ ] every robot query emits {success, timestamp, version, output_format} envelope
  [ ] semantic state values (no UI strings); state classifier shared across queries
  [ ] convergence verified: any two robot queries that should agree DO agree (live probe)
  [ ] backward-compat schemas across CLI minor versions
```

## Reference exemplars (read these before authoring a new CLI)

| CLI | Strength | Path |
|---|---|---|
| `ntm` | Largest reference surface (70+ subcommands), exemplary --help, palette, dashboard, watch modes | `ntm --help` + `ntm <subcmd> --help` |
| `br` (beads) | Doctor + repair, schema emission, JSON envelopes, search, lint | `br --help` |
| `cm` (Jeff's) | Validate/audit/why/undo provenance, --info/--examples self-doc, doctor with --fix | `cm --help` |
| `gh` (GitHub) | Topic-based help, completion, alias system, scriptable JSON | `gh --help` |
| `kubectl` | Resource scoping, dry-run, explain, get -o json discipline | (industry standard) |

## Anti-pattern from session 2026-05-01

The B1.5/B1.5.5 traumas in CASS v2 close-loop demonstrated three of the anti-patterns above:
1. **Console_script name collision** — pyproject.toml proposed `cm = "mem.cli:cli"` while `~/.local/bin/cm` (Jeff's upstream Bun binary) was already in PATH. The correct name is `mem`, matching the package's own docstring (`Usage: mem health, mem search, ...`).
2. **No doctor command** — when adapters failed (list-shadowing in mem.adapters.*), the operator had no way to see "which adapter is failing and why" without diving into Python tracebacks.
3. **No upstream-report path** — bugs in adapters couldn't be classified as local-vs-upstream, so the team had no forcing function to file Jeff issues.

The recovery (file the cm-audit recovery epic) MUST adhere to this skill's standard. Any new CLI work that doesn't is rejected at bead-review.

